Backport of upstream commit c73132272065074d82988a8a987406fd9a66a11a
("Fix permission handling on page copy") to wagtail 4.2.3.

Addresses CVE-2026-44200 (GHSA-67rv-mg8q-5pf3 / PYSEC-2026-149):
permission checks on page copy/alias were too lenient. A CMS user
with limited page access could copy a page they were not allowed to
view (and optionally publish it / create an alias) into an area of
the site where they had add permission, disclosing the source
page's content.

Backport changes:
 - wagtail/models/pages.py in 7.x is wagtail/models/__init__.py
   in 4.2.3 (PagePermissionTester.can_copy / can_copy_to live there).
 - page_permission_policy from wagtail/permissions.py does not exist
   in 4.2.3; the equivalent semantic is
   UserPagePermissionsProxy(user).can_publish_pages().
 - In wagtail/actions/copy_page.py, the equivalent of
   `to.permissions_for_user(self.user)` is
   `UserPagePermissionsProxy(self.user).for_page(to)`; the bug being
   fixed is the use of `self.to` (which can be None) instead of the
   resolved local `to`.
 - Test additions are not ported: 4.2.3's test_copy_page.py and
   test_pages.py have a different fixture layout (no sibling_page,
   different API class hierarchy) so backporting them risks
   unrelated test churn. The behavioural fix is fully covered by
   the source-code changes below.

